Sure thing! Here’s how to tackle each point:

1. Using a breadboard for your capacitor
   • Place the breadboard so that you have one horizontal power rail dedicated to GND and one row for your input signal.  
   • Insert the capacitor so that one leg lives in the same row as your banana’s input alligator clip and the other leg goes into the GND rail.  
   • Clip your input lead to the cap’s signal row and the ground lead to the GND rail. Keep the cap legs as short as possible to minimize additional noise pickup.

2. Choosing the right capacitor type
   • Non-polar ceramics (MLCC) or polyester film capacitors (NP0/C0G) are ideal at 10–22 nF because they’re stable and non-polar.  
   • Electrolytics are polar and typically start in the microfarad range, so they’re not well suited to low-value filtering and can introduce leakage or polarity issues.

3. Simple Arduino debounce example
   If you’re using an Arduino environment, the Bounce2 library makes this trivial:

#include <Bounce2.h>
#define INPUT_PIN 2
Bounce debouncer;

void setup() {
  pinMode(INPUT_PIN, INPUT);
  debouncer.attach(INPUT_PIN);
  debouncer.interval(50);  // 50 ms debounce interval
}

void loop() {
  debouncer.update();
  if (debouncer.fell()) {
    Keyboard.press('A');  // replace with your key mapping
    delay(5);
    Keyboard.releaseAll();
  }
}

   • This code waits 50 ms after the first valid edge before accepting another press. You can tweak interval() to taste.

By using a breadboard or perf board to hold a small ceramic/polyester capacitor, selecting a non-polar part, and adding a short debounce routine in your Arduino sketch, you’ll eliminate most of those phantom triggers—no soldering required. Happy playing!
